Chapter 2: Background and Related Work

This chapter establishes the academic context for Adaptive Sensorimotor Intelligence (ASI). We survey the foundational fields that inform our approach and identify the specific theoretical shortcomings that ASI is designed to overcome. The review is organized into four thematic pillars: (2.1) Classical and Modern Robotic Control, (2.2) Learning for Manipulation and Contact, (2.3) Hybrid Systems and Safety-Critical Control, and (2.4) Meta-Learning and Domain Adaptation. The chapter concludes with a synthesis that defines the precise research gap addressed in Chapter 3.

2.1 Classical and Modern Robotic Control

2.1.1 Model-Based Control and Its Limitations

The bedrock of robotic manipulation is the Lagrangian formulation of rigid-body dynamics:

M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q,\dot{q})\dot{q} + g(q) = \tau + \tau_{ext}

Classical control strategies exploit the structure of this equation. Computed Torque Control [1] uses a model of M, C, and g to exactly cancel the nonlinearities, reducing the system to a double integrator \ddot{q} = u. Impedance Control [2] and Admittance Control [3] regulate the dynamic relationship between force and motion, allowing robots to exhibit compliant behavior.

However, these methods are model-dependent. They require precise knowledge of kinematic and inertial parameters, which may change when the robot grasps an object of unknown mass. More critically, they assume continuous contact dynamics. The transition from free space to rigid constraint is treated as a disturbance to be rejected rather than a fundamental change in the system's degrees of freedom. As noted by [4], standard impedance control can exhibit instability during the impact phase of contact.

2.1.2 Adaptive Control and System Identification

To address parametric uncertainty, Adaptive Control [5] was developed. These methods estimate unknown parameters (e.g., mass, link length) online using recursive least squares or gradient descent and update the control law accordingly. The Slotine-Li adaptive controller [6] provides a Lyapunov-based proof of trajectory tracking convergence despite constant unknown parameters.

Limitations in Context: Standard adaptive control assumes the parameters are constant or slowly varying and that the structure of the dynamics is known. In unstructured manipulation, the parameters (friction coefficient, object geometry) can change abruptly upon contact with a new surface. Furthermore, these methods cannot learn to compensate for unmodeled phenomena like complex friction hysteresis or soft-body deformation from first principles.

2.2 Learning for Manipulation and Contact

2.2.1 Reinforcement Learning (RL) in Robotics

The advent of deep reinforcement learning has enabled robots to learn complex motor skills directly from experience or simulation [7]. Policies \pi_\theta(a|s) are trained to maximize cumulative reward. Model-Free RL algorithms (e.g., PPO, SAC) have demonstrated impressive results in dexterous manipulation, quadrupedal locomotion, and in-hand object reorientation [8].

Limitations in Context (ACT-ROBOT-2026-002):

· Sample Inefficiency: Training contact-rich tasks from scratch in the real world is prohibitively time-consuming and dangerous.
· Sim-to-Real Transfer Gap: Policies trained exclusively in simulation suffer from a reality gap. The visual textures, actuator dynamics, and contact physics (friction, restitution) differ between the simulator and reality. While domain randomization [9] improves robustness by training over a distribution of simulator parameters, it does not eliminate the gap; it merely produces a policy that is conservatively average across the distribution, often sacrificing peak performance for robustness.
· Static Policy Assumption: Most deployed RL policies are frozen after training. They do not adapt online when they encounter an out-of-distribution environment (e.g., an unusually heavy bottle). This violates the requirement for real-time adaptation outlined in the problem statement.

2.2.2 Learning Residuals and Hybrid Architectures

A promising direction to combine the reliability of model-based control with the flexibility of learning is the residual policy approach [10]. Here, the control torque is decomposed as:

\tau = \tau_{model-based} + \pi_{\theta}^{res}(state)

The learned component compensates for unmodeled dynamics or disturbances. This is a direct precursor to our ASI formulation. Recent work has also explored Diffusion Policies [11] for expressing multimodal action distributions, which is crucial for tasks like pushing or insertion where multiple valid contact strategies exist.

Limitations in Context: While effective, these methods lack formal stability guarantees when the residual policy is a deep neural network. Without constraints, a poorly initialized or over-confident residual can destabilize an otherwise stable nominal controller. Our ASI framework addresses this by explicitly bounding the Lipschitz constant of the residual and filtering the combined action through a safety-critical QP.

2.3 Hybrid Systems and Safety-Critical Control

2.3.1 Hybrid Dynamical Systems and Filippov Solutions

The mathematics of contact requires moving beyond smooth ordinary differential equations. Hybrid Dynamical Systems theory [12] provides the formalism for systems with both continuous flows and discrete jumps. The transition from non-contact to contact is a state-dependent switching event.

When the vector field is discontinuous, classical solutions may not exist. Filippov's method [13] extends the notion of a solution by replacing the discontinuous differential equation \dot{x} = f(x) with a differential inclusion \dot{x} \in \mathbf{F}(x), where \mathbf{F}(x) is the convex hull of the limiting vector fields at the discontinuity. This is the rigorous mathematical language required to analyze the stability of robots making and breaking contact—a core element of our model in Section 3.2.

2.3.2 Control Barrier Functions (CBFs) and Control Lyapunov Functions (CLFs)

Control Barrier Functions (CBFs) [14] provide a powerful tool for ensuring safety (i.e., forward invariance of a safe set) in continuous control systems. Given a set \mathcal{C} = \{x \mid h(x) \geq 0\}, a function h is a CBF if there exists a control input such that \dot{h}(x, u) + \kappa h(x) \geq 0.

Control Lyapunov Functions (CLFs) [15] provide a dual tool for ensuring stability (convergence to a goal). By combining CLFs and CBFs into a single Quadratic Program (QP) [16], one can synthesize a controller that minimally modifies a nominal input to satisfy both safety and stability constraints.

Limitations in Context: The standard CLF-CBF-QP framework assumes an accurate model to compute \dot{h} and \dot{V}. In the presence of significant model error (the very problem we face in contact-rich tasks), the QP may become infeasible or the safety guarantees may be violated. Robust CBFs [17] have been proposed to handle bounded disturbances. Our ASI framework integrates this robustness concept with a learned residual, providing the first ISS guarantee for a CBF-protected system that uses online meta-learning.

2.4 Meta-Learning and Domain Adaptation for Robotics

2.4.1 Model-Agnostic Meta-Learning (MAML)

The requirement to "learn new tasks dynamically" points toward Meta-Learning. MAML [18] is an algorithm for learning a model initialization \theta that can adapt to a new task with only a few gradient steps. The bi-level optimization objective is:

\min_\theta \sum_{\mathcal{T}_i} \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{T}_i}(\theta - \alpha \nabla_\theta \mathcal{L}_{\mathcal{T}_i}(\theta))

In robotics, MAML has been used to enable rapid adaptation of locomotion policies to changes in terrain or payload [19].

Limitations in Context: MAML is typically an offline meta-training algorithm. The inner loop adaptation happens during a dedicated adaptation phase, not continuously during task execution. Our ASI framework extends this to continuous online adaptation (the slow timescale), requiring a new analysis of dynamic regret to ensure the updates do not interfere with the fast stability loop.

2.4.2 PAC-Bayesian Generalization Bounds for Sim-to-Real

A rigorous understanding of the sim-to-real gap requires statistical learning theory. PAC-Bayes theory [20] provides bounds on the generalization error of randomized classifiers. Recent work [21, 22] has applied PAC-Bayes to RL policies, bounding the difference between simulated and real-world returns based on the KL divergence between the training distribution P (augmented with domain randomization) and the posterior distribution over policies Q found during adaptation.

Synthesis and Research Gap: The literature contains separate, highly advanced components: robust CBFs for safety, meta-learning for fast adaptation, and PAC-Bayes for generalization analysis. However, no existing work unifies these components within a single mathematically certified framework for hybrid contact dynamics. The ASI architecture and its accompanying theorems, presented in the following chapter, provide this missing synthesis. We prove that by imposing a two-timescale structure and a Lipschitz constraint on the learned residual, we can simultaneously achieve ISS (via CBF/CLF), bounded regret (via meta-learning), and certified sim-to-real transfer (via PAC-Bayes) for the specific failure mode identified in ACT-ROBOT-2026-002.



